{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1bfd0f45-8941-4ae4-8321-c9d495ed3254","content":"In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` ties the lifetime to an **HTTP request** — each request gets a fresh instance. In MAUI, there's no equivalent request boundary. The app has a single long-lived scope, so `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton` — your DbContext lives for the entire app session.\n\n**Fixes:**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient`** — gives a new DbContext each time one is injected. Be mindful of disposing it yourself.\n\n2. **Create scopes manually** using `IServiceScopeFactory`:\n   ```csharp\n   using var scope = scopeFactory.CreateScope();\n   var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n\n3. **Use a DbContext factory** (recommended):\n   ```csharp\n   // Registration\n   builder.Services.AddDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>(opts =>\n       opts.UseSqlite(\"...\"));\n\n   // Usage in a page/viewmodel\n   using var db = dbContextFactory.CreateDbContext();\n   ```\n\nOption 3 (`IDbContextFactory`) is the cleanest pattern for MAUI — it makes lifetime explicit and avoids stale tracked entities leaking across navigations.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"07cfe00c-43d7-49b9-8eb2-8edf2f3e0520","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common issue when transitioning from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping. This is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to look at any code.\n\nThe key issue: In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance per HTTP request (each request is a \"scope\"). In MAUI, there's no equivalent of an HTTP request to define a scope boundary. By default, MAUI has a single scope for the entire application lifetime, making `AddScoped` behave essentially like `AddSingleton`.","outputTokens":440,"requestId":"A859:1BCBFD:6E9242:7FCF22:69FBE50A"},"id":"8008a57b-2860-4bb7-a57e-b634061f1a0e","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:04:21.990Z","parentId":"dacf745a-9632-41e8-83b4-995037c251f9"}
